## Project structure

```
DocuRAG/
├── src/
│   ├── document_loader.py   # Loads PDF/TXT files and splits into chunks
│   ├── vector_store.py      # Embeds chunks and builds the FAISS index
│   ├── generator.py         # Generates answers using Flan-T5 or OpenAI
│   └── rag_pipeline.py      # End-to-end pipeline connecting all components
├── notebooks/
│   └── DocuRAG_Colab.ipynb  # Step-by-step walkthrough in Google Colab
├── data/                    # Place your documents here
├── app.py                   # Streamlit web app
└── requirements.txt
```

---

## Getting started

**Run in Google Colab** — open `notebooks/DocuRAG_Colab.ipynb`, all packages install automatically.

**Run locally**

```bash
git clone https://github.com/IlaInnovates/DocuRAG.git
cd DocuRAG
pip install -r requirements.txt
streamlit run app.py
```

Open `http://localhost:8501`, upload a document, and start asking questions.

**Use as a library**

```python
from src.rag_pipeline import RAGPipeline

pipe = RAGPipeline()
pipe.ingest("report.pdf")

answer = pipe.ask("What are the key findings?")
print(answer)
```

---

## Tech stack

| Component | Tool |
|---|---|
| Embeddings | `sentence-transformers` — `all-MiniLM-L6-v2` |
| Vector search | `faiss-cpu` — cosine similarity |
| Answer generation | `transformers` — `google/flan-t5-base` |
| PDF reading | `pymupdf` |
| Web interface | `streamlit` |

---

## Why I built this

I wanted to understand RAG from scratch — so I built every component separately instead of using a framework. This gave me a clear picture of how chunking, embedding quality, and retrieval precision each affect the final answer.

